## 窶亀he Recap: A Viral Headache

窶亀here is something inherently terrifying about a superhero whose greatest enemy isn窶冲 a guy in a yellow suit or a telepathic gorilla, but a viral hashtag. In The Flash #32, writer Ryan North and artist Gavin Guidry deliver a story that feels painfully modern, hilariously frantic, and deeply rooted in what makes Wally West the most relatable speedster in the DC Multiverse.

窶鬼ince North took over the title with issue #31, there窶冱 been a palpable shift in energy. We窶况e moved away from the high-concept, cosmic horror "cosmic weirdness" of previous runs and back into the street-level (well, high-speed street-level) charm that defined the Waid and Johns eras. Issue #32, titled "Speed Shots," is the definitive proof that this new creative team knows exactly how to handle the "Fastest Man Alive" when he窶冱 being slowed down by the sheer absurdity of human nature.

窶亀he premise of this issue is a stroke of genius that feels like it should have happened years ago. An anonymous, shady online content creator has launched a contest: $10,000 to anyone who captures high-quality footage of themselves being rescued by the Flash.

窶起aturally, Central City has descended into absolute chaos.

窶亀he issue opens with Wally West being run ragged. He窶冱 not fighting the Rogues or stopping a bank heist; he窶冱 essentially playing the world窶冱 most dangerous game of "Catch the Influencer." Civilians are throwing themselves off rooftops, jumping in front of moving buses, and dangling from cranes窶蚤ll while holding their phones at the perfect angle for that sweet, sweet engagement.

窶妓ally is exhausted. He窶冱 missing family dinners every fifteen seconds, his stress levels are through the roof, and he窶冱 starting to question his "no-judgment" policy. Just as he窶冱 reaching his breaking point, he spots a familiar face on a ledge: Leonard Snart, a.k.a. Captain Cold. But Snart isn't there for the prize money. He窶冱 there because he has a warning that makes the "Clout Crisis" look like a walk in the park.

