## 窶亀he Story: Character Over Chaos

![](https://images.squarespace-cdn.com/content/v1/5d56e145f80b7500016ba502/1f6dafec-7195-41a1-9d12-bff20bfd4c4c/1000014820.jpg)

窶騎yan North has a specific gift for writing dialogue that feels like a real conversation, even when one participant is moving at Mach 5. What makes the story in #32 work isn't just the humor窶杯hough there are some genuine laugh-out-loud moments regarding the "Flash-Tok" trend窶琶t窶冱 the way North centers Wally窶冱 humanity.

窶妓ally West has always been the "Blue Collar Flash." Unlike Barry Allen, who often feels like a scientific icon, Wally is a dad, a husband, and a guy who just wants to finish his sandwich. Seeing his frustration boil over as he rescues the 50th person of the hour is incredibly satisfying. It窶冱 a meta-commentary on our current attention economy, but it never feels like a lecture. It feels like a genuine obstacle for a hero who can be everywhere at once but can窶冲 be responsible for everyone窶冱 common sense.

窶亀he real meat of the story, however, is the team-up. The dynamic between Wally and Leonard Snart is legendary, and North leans into the "respectful enemies" trope with perfection. Snart窶冱 "hard reset" back to a man with a code is a welcome change. Their snarky back-and-forth as they investigate the source of the contest provides the issue窶冱 best beats. When they realize the contest isn't just about views窶杯hat it窶冱 actually a cover for something much more sinister窶杯he stakes shift from "social media satire" to "cataclysmic threat" with surprising grace.

